{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580928/1945101201/0327.xml":{"full_text":"SUMMIT COUNTY LABOR NEWS\nPublished Every Friday by\nTHE SUMMIT COUNTY LABOR KfiWS\nA Non-Partisan Newspaper published in the best interests of Or\nganized Labor and the entire Coinmuhity.\nEditorial, Advertising and Printing Offices\n920 SOUTH HIGH STREET Telephone\u2014FR-5155\n__AKKOX 11. OHIO__\nALEX EIGEXMACHT__Editor and Publisher\nEntered as Second Class Matter May 4. 1923, at Post Office at\nAkron, Ohio, under the Act of March 3, 1897\nYearly Subscription in Advance___$2.00\nSi* Months _;_*_a_$1.00\nThe Summit County Labor Newt accepts advertisements front' firms not\non the unfair list of the Central Bodies. It musi be understood, however, that\nthe editorial policy of this publication it affected in no'-way by such advertise\nments.\nNews of interest from the various local unions under the jurisdiction of the\nCongress of Industrial Organizations. Akron Industrial Union Council and the\nAmerican Federation of Labor and the Trades and Labor Assembly is solicited.\nAll news matter should reach the editorial office of the Summit County Labor\nNews not later than Tuesday.\nCongress Declares Wair dii Laboi*\nFourteen reactionary representatives put Congress in the posi\ntion of declaring war on labor unions. They voted down 10 other\nmembers of the Ways and Means Committee and said there would\nhe no unemployment compensation hill until strikes cease.\nTheir excuse was that it is impossible to tell w hat the unemploy\nment situation is until strikes are over. That is a thin one. Congress\ndid not even wait until the war was over to protect industry .with bil\nlions against reconversion losses.\n'This is a club held over the head of labor which is not apt to at\ntain its purposes. Kverytmc knew that when the war was ended\nlabor would have to use its economic weapon to obtain adjustment of\ngrievances and wage questions.\nLittle faith is held in the ability of the War Labor Board to en\nenforce its directives and it is not accepting new dispute cases where\nboth parties do not agree to abide by its verdicts.\nWhat is labor to do\u2014wait until later when its strength has\ndwindled and its resources have drained away, to make a battle for\nw'hat it considers a just postwar setup?\nLabor knows too well what happened to it after the last war.\nIf take-home pay is drastically reduced now. as industry desires,\nunions will face a long battle to ever regain the ground lost. It is\nlabor's argument that industry can pay high wages without raising\nprices, if production is sufficiently high. That is good business for\neveryone. Workers cannot buy goods to consume high production\nunless their wages are up.\nThe Way of Wage Increases'\nWe set by the papers, as someone or the other said, that the CIO\nis at it again. Strikes, strikes, and more strikes. At least, that is the\npage one feature of practically every daily that you happen to read.\nHUT! Nary a line about the demands of manufacturers and industry\nfor higher prices do you see. Oh. no. that would be stepping on the\ntoes of the big boys, and the daily press in Akron couldn't afford to\ndo that.\nOn every hand, we see where, ceilings are being raised on this or\nthat article by the Ol\u2019A, and we see continually nudging of prices on\nthe very necessities of life, hut you don\u2019t see scare headlines about it.\nLabor today is asking for general wage increases. In the CIO\nthe UAWA is asking for a 30% increase in wage rates. The Steel\nworkers and the Electrical Workers are asking for $2.00 per day in\ncrease. These increases are desired for one specific purpose. TO\nCOMPENSATE TOR TUI*: REDUCTION IN HOURS WORKED\nPER WEEK. AND TO MAINTAIN THU LEVEE OE \"TAKE\nHOME\" PAY.\nAs a result of Labor making these economic demands, in order\nto live as decent American citizens should, the great mass of the\ngeneral public is being misled. Sure, strikes are occurring and are\nthreatened, but the daily press is distorting the actual facts.\nA great part of the general public who are not .members of or\nganized labor, but who should be oitr friends, are forming their!\nviews from the prejudiced dfiily press. As a result. Labor is casti\ngated bv the merchants, doe\u2019tors. lawyers, salesmen and members of\nwhite collar groups who are unorganized. HUT. do these same peo\nple realize their economic security in a large sense depends upon the j\neconomic welfare of the workers in the mills.-shops and factories: j\nThe economic success of the average farmer depends to a great ex\ntent upon the ability of the average industrial worker to buy what\nthe farmer produces, and at a good price.\nEvery worker who is a member of organized Labor should say\nto his grocer, his doctor, his dentist, the dry cleaner, the baker and\nall others with whom he deals, and who depend upon him and his eo\nworkers for their livelihood, \"Look, Mister, what I am going to\nspend with \\ou in the coining year depends upon how much I wil'\nearn. That means that during the war I have been making pretty\ngood money, and I have bought my share of war bonds, too. I spent\na lot of what I made with yon. blit now that longer hours and over\ntime pay is out, my income is down to.$25 and $30 per week: I\u2019ll just\nhave to-spend as little with you as 1 possibly can. Now. you are going\nto feel the effects of cutbacks and reconversion along with us work\nmg stiffs.\"\n\"You say that some of the CIO is on strike, and that I might'he\non strike, too. Sure, that is possible, hut right now we want to tell\nvo.u that being on strike is no picnic. We don't strike just for the\nhell of it. We strike to preserve our way of life, to maintain our\nhomes and to raise our kids to be good citizens. What we win. by\nstriking, in the way of economic gains, also benefits you aiid you\nshould be on otir side in this sera]).\"\nPerhaps then you get this tossed at you./'Higher wdges means\ninflation. If your wages go up, then my prices go up. and neither of\nUs wins anything.\u201d\nThere is the basis of your argument. Labor contends, and rightly\nso. that the economic^future of our nation rests on good wages and\nhigh .production, by not only maintaining the so-called American\nstandard of living, but of increasing it. through better schools, ade\nquate medical cart*, more and better housing, all of which in turn\ncreates more and more jobs. Through high volume of goods pro\nduced and sold, profits are maintained without inflation anil price\nraising.\nLabor was held to 1.5% wage increases during the war. The high\n\"take home\u201d pay envelope came for overtime premium pay and\nlonger hours, which no longer exist. Tlie Cost of .Living, however,\ndid not stay at a 15% increase but soared to almost a 50% increase.\nThe gap created by the ever-increasing cost of living must be wiped\nout while peacetime wage rates are being established now, or it will\nnever be in balance again.\nOnly through high wages and production, will we as a nation be\nAble to maintain \"our economic balance and be able to pity off tlie^\ntremendous cost of World War If. Let u,s all get together dri a sound\neconomic program, Jobs for All at Good Wages.\nGOV. LAUSCHE\u2019S RECORD\n(Continued from Pa^e 1)\nK'tive grudging support to $21 for 22 week* instead of back\ning the full $25/26 bill. His support to Labot Was too little\nand too late.\nAs the Governors first year drfcws to a close, we find\nhim as sensitive as ever to what he likes to call \u201cpressure\".\nW hat he means by \u201cpressure\" is a group of people seeking\nhis leadership for their cause. He once turned on a Labor\ngroup with the accusation that Labor was trying to pres\nsure him. He was then asked. \u201cDo you object to the voice of\nthe people?\u201d He did not reply. In this regard it is notable\nthat the Chamber of Commerce and Big Business dbn\u2019t seem\nto irritate the Governor as much as those who elected him\nto office.\n11 has been remarked that the Governor is attempting\nto win friends and influence people on the Republican side:\nWith sufch strength\u2014added to Labor\u2019s vote in his pocket\u2014\nhe would be assured of re-election. This may be an unfair\n\u2022stimate, but we record it. The Governor certainly is erring if\nlid assumes that he can be all things to all people and that by\nukewarm liberality he can pacify those who hopefully elect\ned him.\nJames -Garfield Stewart almost defeated Lausche. Re\ncently at a Labor meeting. Stewart was being joshed about\nhis connections with the Republican machine. Stewart drily\n\u2022eplied, \"it seems to me that your Governor seems more at\nhome at a\u2019banquet of the Chamber of Commerce than at a\nUnion meeting.\" That one struck home. There was no reply\nto the defeated Republican candidate who was attending a\nLabor meeting.\nHUBER WINS FRIENDS\nIN CAPITOL MARCH\n(Continued from Page One)\nno interest in opinions of the delega\ntion, sending out word that he was\ntoo busy. Similar expressions were\ndrawn front other Republican Con\ngressmen. Representative John \\'orys\nof Columbus was typical, calling: the\nhull h.inployment Hill \"communistic\u2019\u2019\nand Haunting his contempt for the\nworkers of Ohio.\n\"The delegates from all over Ohio\nCIO TO BROADCAST\nWAR FUND SHOW\nWith liroadway and Hollywood\nstars participating, CIO and industrial\nmanagement October 15 will broad\ncast ,i joint appeal on behalf of the\nNational War Fund' Campaign on a\nnation-wide network of the American\nbroadcasting Company.\nNational President Philip Murray\nwill speak for ClO, and Gerard\nSwope. General Electric President, for\nmanagement.\nThe show will he presented from\n9:30 to 9:55 p.m\u201e Eastern Standard\nTime, originating in New York, Hol\nlywood and Washington. Eouis Cal\njhern, leading figure of stage, screen\nand radio will lie master of ceremon\nies. Taking part in the New York\nportion of the broadcast will be Helen\nHayes, presenting a dramatization\nhighlighting the need for continued\nsupport of many home front and for\neign projects maintained by the Na\ntional War Fund. The broadcast was\nprepared by the National CIO Yvar\nRelief Committee.\nj made I lie. trip homeward considerably\nj sobered. They had been'met by a\nstone wall of indifference and reac\ntion. They bad learned where they\nmissed the boat in '44 and where they\nshould take the boat in \u20194b.\u201d\nThe Akron delegation was among\nthe best received from the three states\nin Washington. Ilass will give a re\nport on the \"March\u201d tonight at the\nregular business meeting of Atron In\ndustrial Union Council during which\nlie will tell of the part played by Con\ngressman Huber.\nThe \"Marche1 conducted last week\nby representatives of the three states\nis part of a nation-wide campaign\nbeing conducted by national CIO of\nficers in the interests of adequate em\nployment compensation and the pro\ngram for ftO million postwar jobs.\nAFL Body Will\nResume Meetings\nRegular business meetings of the\nTrades and Uabor Assembly of Sum\nmit County on the third Thursday\nnight of each month which were can\ncelled during the summer months will\nbe resumed this month, it has been\nannounced by President Murray.\nThe next regular business meeting\nof the body will be held on October\n17th. The meetings scheduled for the\nthird Thursday night in. July, August\nand September were cancelled in or\nder to give delegates a summer vaca\ntion.\n\u00b0Z THE OWNERSHIP. MANAGEMENT. CIRCULATION,\nETC., REQUIRED BY THE ACT OF CONGRESS OF AUGUST 24, 1912.\nOf Summit County Labor News, published Weekly jit Akron, Ohio, for\nOctober 1. 1945.\nStite of Ohio\nComity of Summit)\nBefore me a Notary Public in and for the State arid County aforesaid,\npersonally appeared Alex Eigenmacht. who. having been duly sWnrh accordinf i\nto law, deposes and says that he is the owner and publisher of The Summit\nCounty Labor News and that the following is to the best of his knowledge and\nj belief, a true statement of the ownership, management (and if a daily paper,\nthe circulation), etc., of thj aforesaid publication for the date shown in the\naboye cation required by the Act of August 24. 1912, embodied in section\n411- Postal Laws and Regulations, printed on the reverse of this form, to wit:\nThat the namea and addresses of the publisher, editor, managing editor\nand business manager are:\nPublisher\u2014Alex Eigenmacht. 920 South High Street, Akron, Ohio.\nEditor\u2014Alex Eigenmacht, 920 South High Street.\nManaging Editor\u2014Alex Eigenmacht. 920 South High Street, Akron. Ohio.\nZ. That the oWner is: .(If owned by a corporation, its name and address\nmu*J J, *u,ed \u00abna *1*0 immediately thereunder the names and addresses of\nstockholders, owning or holding one per cent or more of total amount\nof stock. If not owned by a corporation, the names and addresses of the indi\nvidual owners must be given. If owned by a firm, company, or other uniUcor\nporated concern, its n&me arid Address, as well as those oj each individual mem*\nber, must be given.)\nAlex Eigenmacht, 920 South High Street. Akron, Ohio.\nf,..That the known bondholders, mortgagees, ami other Security holder*\n\u00b0r holding 1 per cent of more of total amount of bonds, mortgages\nor other securities afe: (If there are none, so state)\nNone.\nj- That **ie tw0 Paragraph\u2019s next above, giving the names of the owners,\nstockholders, and security holders, if any, contain not only th* liit of Stock\nholders ind security holders as they appear upon the books of the company\nbut also, in cases where the stockholder or security holder appear upon the\nbooks of the company as trustee or in any other fiduciary relation, the name\nof the person or corporation for whom such trustee is acting, is given; also that\nthe said two paragraphs contain statements embracing iffiant\u2019s full knowledge\nanil belief as to the circumstances anil conditions under \"which stockholders and\niecitrity holders who do not appear upon the hook of the company as trustee*,\nhold stock and security in a capacity other than that of a bona fide owner; and\nthis affiant has no reason to believe that any other person association, or Cor\nporation. hi|s any interest direct or Indirect in the said, stock, bonds, or othet\nsecurities than as So stated by him.\n5. That the average number of copies t>f each issue of this^publication\nsold or distributed, through the mails or otherwise, to paid subscribers during\nthe twelve^ months preceding the date shown above is ___\n(This information is required froth daily publications only)\nAlex Eigenmacht.\nSworn to and subscribed before me this 1st day of October, 1945.\nJOHN F. DELANEY, Notary Public.\nMy Commission Expires February, 1946.\nOctober 1. 1944.\nSworn th aiul siibacrlb#A bdfote the tills Srd day of October, 1944.\nt\nJOB BILLS\n(Continued from Page One)\nbill was still waiting for the firSt\nstage pt committee hearings, after the\nSenate had passed a watered down ver\nsion of the measure. Current predic\ntions are that the House Committee\non Executive Expenditures, which is\nhandling tile bill, will not get down\nto it until towards the end of the\nmonth.\nThe Senate version of the bill, de\nscribed by Majority Leader Sen. Bark\nley (D. Ky.) as guaranteeing \u201cevery\nbody out of work the right to seek a\njob if he can find one.\u201d was passe^\nby a vote of 71 to 10. At Sen. Taft's\n(R., O.) insistence it contains an\namendment limiting government ac\ntion to a point consistent with the\ngovernment\u2019s financial obligations.\nAccording to Taft, this amendment\n\"kills the compensatory spending\ntheory. Federal spending as a remedy\nfor unemployment will now' only be\nconsistent with the needs and obliga\ntions of the Federal government- and\nother essential considerations of na\ntional policy.\u201d\nUnder this verbiage lies one of\nTaft's main objectives in what passes\nwith him for public office\u2014the objec\ntive of preventing any real action to\nprovide jobs, where needed, through\ngovernment action.\nOn the House'side. Rep. George\n(Jutland (L)., Cal.), leader of Sortie 115\nRepresentatives who* have pledged to\nfight for a real jobs-for-all hill, in\ndicated that his group will press for\na return to the hill as originally writ\nten.\nThe committee in charge\u2014House\nExecutive Expenditures\u2014is not ex\npected to he too eager to report out\nthe original hill. Letters to your own\nCongressman urging him to join the\ngroup supporting tile hill will help.\nIn a side action oh the unemploy\nment compensation hill, Sen. Murray\n(D., Mont.) has put in a hill (S-1456)\nto put t.ie U. S. Employment Service\nback under Federal management. Tbi,s\nis aimed to undo Sen. Lucas\u2019s (D.,\n111.) amendment returning USES to\nstate patronage machines.\nNEW TAX BILL\n(Continued from Page One)\n5. Freeze social security taxes at\none per cent, despite the fact that they\nhave bien supposed to increase to 2.5\nper cent for the past four years. This\nhas the effect of keeping social secur\nity funds at current levels, rather than\nallowing them to expand.\n6. Repeal the capital stock tax,\nwhich saves corporations another esti\nmated $200,000,000.\nThe report was rushed through se\ncret sessions of the committee in the\nrecord breaking time of four days. Ac\ntion is expected on the House floor by\nnext week, with the Senate Finance\nCommittee expected to do a similar\nrush job on its version of the bill.\npespite a plea for open hearings\nfrom the CIO. sent to Chairman\nDoughlon of the House Committee in\na letter front Nathan Cowan, the com\nmittee held all its hearings in secret,\nwith no chance for labor or other or\nganizations to testify.\nOut of these secret hearings came\nstories\u2014with tile evidence of the re\nported bill to back them up\u2014that the\nRepublicans, with the aid of' Dough\nton, completely dominated the hear\nings. Though they did not get tile-20\nper cent straight across the board in\ncome tax reduction they were aiming\nfor, they got half of it, with the\nstrong possibility that tlie Senate will\nboost it higher.\nThey also got a sizable hunk of the\ngravy they wanted for the corpora\ntions on the cut in the excess profits\ntax from 95 to 60 per cent\u2014a cut that\nwill save the corporations over half'\nof the amoudt they have been paying.\nARMY CONTINUES\nFAMILY HELP\nFamily allowances are being au\nthorized for dependents of all men\nnow enlisting or being inducted into\nthe Army, it was announced today by\nllrig.-Gen. Leonard H. Sims. USA,\nDirector of the War Department Of\nfice of Dependency Benefits. T hat\nactivity of the Office of the Fiscal Di\nrector, Headquarters, Army Service\nForces, located in Newark. NeW Jer\nsey, administers soldiers\u2019 benefits for\nthe entire Army.\n\u201cThe Servicemen\u2019s Dependents Al\nlowance Act of 1942, as amended is\nstill in effect,\u201d General Sims stated.\n\"Under this law, wives, children, de\npendent parents and other dependents\nof all enlisted men and women and\naviation cadets are entitled to family\nallowances.\nI\nDischarge 6-1*5\nBy Mail, CIO\nTells Army J\n(Continued from Page One)\ning shall have been completed, when\nthe discharge papers, the Army,\nSeparation Qualification Record, his\nfinal pay and allowances, and any\nI thing else would have be mailed to\nhim.\nSome of this, such as the last\ntwo installations of the mustering oot\npay, is mailed under the present sys\ntem. and the soldier has the option\nof having all his money sent by check\nand mail. The same thing can be done\nfrom the camp as well as from the\nseparation center.\"\nPointing to the fact that Separa\ntion Centers are only temporary fa\ncilities to be discontinued January 1,\n1946. Golden continued:\n\u201cOur proposal would make it pos\nsible to send home every GI almost\nas soon as his services can be dis\npensed with. And the faster the sur\nplus soldiers can he discharged, the\nhigher the morale and the efficiency\nof those who remain.\n\u201cThe Army has exercised consider\nable flexibility in the field, when fac\ned by an emergency. The same kind\nof thinking that speeded up victory,\ncan be used to speed up demobilwa\ntioif.\u201d\nVeteran of several Pacific cam\npaigns and before enlistment a mem\nber of the staff of the CIO Steelwork\ners, Meyer Bernstein has been named\nassistant to Clinton S. Golden, chair\nman of the CTO Veterans Committee.\nSave Your Bonds!\nteed aHewloftmi?\nTHE PICKINGS ARE PLENTIFUL\nAT CARLTON'S!\nAIL \\IRGIX WOOL Gabardines, Cavalry Twills, Tweeds,\nCoverts. Camel Hair Fleeces! Advance styles, tailored with a\nmaster touch And at our old low prewar prices, you're bound\nto save RLAL DOUGH on these Topcoats of famous Carlton\nQuality. Cash in now!\nSWEET SAVINGS AT\nt1 x\nTO $39.50\nCHARGE ACCOUNT OR BUDGET SERVICE AVAILABLE\nCARLTONS\n201 SOUTH MAIN ST.\nJust In! A New Shipment of\nUNPAINTED CHESTS\n*v V\nA. 23% in. it-We, 12 in. deep,\n29% in. trill, 3 drawers\nII. 23% in. wide. 12 in. deep,\n42 in. tall, 5 drawers\n*5.99\n*9-98\nC. 23% in. wide, 12 in. deep,\n3-1% in. tidl, 4 drawers\n-All these handy little chests are smoothly sand\ned all ready for you to paint. Just the\nthings for children\u2019s room or guest room, cot\ntages and student ilorni rooms.\nO'NEIL'S FOR HOUSEWARES-FOURTH FLOOR\nO\u2019NEIL Co.","height":"27428","width":"21700"}}
